Like let's not even go there, but on the main docker images, you know?

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:09.880
Yeah.

00:20:10.110 --> 00:20:10.220
Yeah.

00:20:10.240 --> 00:20:13.680
Yeah, I mean, the slow rollout is definitely a big part of it, right?

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:17.740
Like a lot of people get their Python not direct from the source.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:27.440
They get it from a distribution or they get it from Amazon Linux with Python or whatever, right?

00:20:27.620 --> 00:20:29.060
Like it's a distribution of Python.

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:30.080
Or brew install.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:32.380
Brew install Python, yeah.

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:35.700
So a lot of people are not living on the edge.

00:20:36.560 --> 00:20:39.240
And I think that that helps in a way.

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:44.760
obviously people that are living on the edge maybe they're the more valuable targets but

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:53.280
I mean I'm not going to be the one to to encourage that um yeah I I don't think that

00:20:53.970 --> 00:20:58.660
I think the biggest defenses against this and this was what was discussed there was

00:20:59.450 --> 00:21:04.460
trying to push things to be in the open and actually in a way open source is uniquely

00:21:05.140 --> 00:21:10.120
able to respond. Right, right, right, right. Defended against for these sorts of attacks.

00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:17.660
Because if this were to happen in Windows, for example, like, would we have had the almost

00:21:18.200 --> 00:21:24.420
immediate, like, being able to debug what the actual attack was, how long this had been going on,

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:30.160
what patches were bad, right? Like that, that sort of visibility into the source code is

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:33.560
something that was really important in being able to actually track this thing down.

00:21:34.639 --> 00:21:42.320
and so like having test files and binary files not checked into source code and instead generated

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:47.700
so one of the parts of this attack that allowed it to go hidden for so long and be checked into

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:54.560
source code was that all almost all of the attack code was hidden extremely well in a binary file

00:21:55.659 --> 00:22:01.120
which made it so that code reviewers some of the test binary uh elements because if you got a

00:22:01.060 --> 00:22:06.200
compression file utility, you got to have compressed files for your unit test, right?

00:22:06.919 --> 00:22:12.140
Exactly. So it was basically these files were checked in. And there's the just huge binary

00:22:12.460 --> 00:22:18.260
blobs that you can't actually get your eyeballs on to review. We talk about like lots of eyeballs

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:23.620
make for shallow bugs. Well, if the eyeballs can't see the bugs, then you're not going to find them.

00:22:23.810 --> 00:22:29.820
And so we talked about like, removing binary files from the source code or making sure that

00:22:29.780 --> 00:22:33.200
all the binary files that are generated have like a script that allows them to

00:22:33.210 --> 00:22:35.300
be generated at any time and things like that.

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:38.860
So is it one of the changes recently?

00:22:38.930 --> 00:22:42.280
I can't remember if this was on PI PI or if this is a GitHub thing,

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:47.080
but allowing GitHub to be the thing that publishes directly,

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:54.020
builds the wheels and uploads them to PI PI rather than somebody downloading

00:22:54.090 --> 00:22:55.800
the code, building them and uploading it,

00:22:56.160 --> 00:22:58.880
which obviously that's a opaque step there.

00:22:59.740 --> 00:23:06.480
Yeah. So other, like other things that tie more strongly, these, whatever release artifacts are

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:11.340
actually ending up on people's machines to the source code. So that's, I mean, I would call that

00:23:11.500 --> 00:23:16.440
build provenance. There's a whole bunch of different frameworks that that works under,

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:21.260
but yeah, build provenance, being able to tie in an artifact that's installed in your system back to

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:28.080
the actual source code so that when you are evaluating that, that artifact on whether you

00:23:27.980 --> 00:23:32.640
you want to install that on your system or deciding whether to upgrade or whatever, you

00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:36.640
can look at the source code instead of looking at this compiled binary.

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:41.260
That's something that I really want to focus on for PyPI in the future, but yeah, we're

00:23:41.260 --> 00:23:41.680
not there yet.

00:23:41.840 --> 00:23:41.940
Awesome.

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:42.460
Yeah.

